segments.text: My dad was at the Air Force War College on his way to Vietnam.
We drove over to Maxwell Air Force Base after graduation before I even shipped out, and my mom and dad gave us this Morris Minor, a little English car.
Nancy and I were driving back through Mobile.
It had an electrical fuel pump in it, and those points would stick.
So I was going over the bridge.
This is where the tunnel was there, and I was going over the bridge,
And as I went up, that damn thing was sticking, so I was having to open and close the door to give it enough of a shock to stick.

And then I thought, well, I'll pull over here in a parking place, and I'll just tie a string onto it where I can just yank that string, because we've got a long ways to go to Galveston, Texas, from Mobile, Alabama.
Well, as I'm sitting there, and there was a Texas Aggie thing in back window.
As I'm sitting there in Mobile, Alabama, just in this parking lot, somebody drives by, Texas Aggie, says, hey, need any help?
I said, no, I don't.
We talked for a while.
But, I mean, that's gone on.
When I, more recently, as Director for Operations out at U.S. Inc. PAC, my, I had a Marine Lieutenant Colonel that worked for me, Dave Close, who's just an absolute Texas gentleman.
Just one of the nicest men you'll ever meet in your life.
Tough, tough Marine.
But it was Dave that came up with the strategy that we used in East Timor.
We were sitting around my office.
And I was lamenting how I didn't want to do like we did in Bosnia and get bogged down.

I wanted to have some sort of a rotational presence where we used deployed forces to go in, get those guys with the machetes, get the Australians in there to run the operation because they're always prancing around saying they ought to be doing stuff.
And Dave was the one that took that vision and made it a strategy, which even George Bush has talked about.
And really a great guy.
So Texas Aggies have been...
Of course, in my squadron, I mentioned I had an executive officer just everywhere you go.
I always, in the military, I knew I could take an Aggie aside and say, hey, I really need your help on this one.
I can't explain why, but go work it.
There's just that special relationship.
It didn't matter if the guy was an ensign.
our second lieutenant, we had a relationship, which you just don't develop with other folks.
You do it immediately.
And you know that what you're going to get back is going to be truthful.
It's going to be ethical.
It's going to be the right thing to do from what they know, from what they're working with.
So, no, I think it's just marvelous.
I will tell you, though, today, walking across campus, I haven't walked across this direction probably in, gosh, 30-something years.
And I was just amazed at the number of people that just walked by and,
didn't say hi or anything.
I mean, it really kind of took me back.
You know, I felt kind of silly saying howdy or how you doing, you know, and they just kind of look at you and walk on.
So we've lost a little of that, I think, around here, which is a shame.
Have lost some, but still compared to the other campuses that I know of.
Yeah, I mean, there was no unfriendliness about it, but I just didn't feel the same.
And it used to be, you know, you'd see an Aggie, you know, hey, Giggleman.
You don't see much of that anymore.
Everybody kind of looks at you.
Some of those things have gone, which I think is a shame, but that's all part of growth.
We were only 8,000 people in those days here, I think, in 64, 65.
Now the entering freshman class is that big.
Did you ever lose your ring?
Knock on wood.
I flew combat with it.
That ring, I wouldn't even think of getting in a jet.

uh... without my ring on i'd never in fact it was a thing in the military they didn't want you to wear rings for a lot of reasons if you're shot down it's got your name in it and which was always kind of stupid because name rank and serial numbers which you got to give the guys and plus i never thought the suckers could shoot me down but they were you know they they were afraid to get caught on something as you're climbing in out of the airplane but i i always flew with my ring i never ever went into combat or even flew an airplane without my ring i had to get it enlarged a little bit but
Never went anywhere without it.
Now, thinking about other traditions, you didn't have senior boots, did you?
No, and that was always, you know, like I told you, we thought, boy, we really racked our brains.
But can you imagine the Navy blues with boots on?
You looked just like a Gestapo officer.
And, you know, think about it.
That was only 20-something years after the war.
And that was a big deal.
You know, we just didn't want to.
We didn't want to do that, but I've always, always, always regretted that.
Did you all come up here for final review?
Oh, you bet.
Yes, sir.
I would assume they... Well, of course, I don't know what their core is down there now, but everybody was in the core down there, and yes, we did.
We sure did.
The changes about co-education and all that came about while you were a student.
Absolutely.
What did you and your buddies think about those changes?
You know, when you were telling that story here a minute ago about General Rudder, I...
You know, that never bothered us, or it never seemed to.
I don't recall anybody jumping up and down about it.
And you know, an interesting thing about that, when we started bringing women into the military, it went, and I recall it going so well here.
Of course, it really happened after I left.
But I always thought it was the right thing to do.
And, you know, and...
When we started bringing women onto combat ships and so forth, I had command of Mars in Desert Storm and had the first women in combat.
And I went back and talked to Admiral Borda, who was a subsequent CNO that shot himself, and he was going to tell me how to do it.
And I said, wait a minute, Admiral, you know, this is not a difficult thing to do.
You know, you respect people for what they can do, not for what they are or who they are or how they came about.
And that's the way you handle it.
You don't have to go build special spaces.
On my ship, I've got a Velcro thing up there because you only have so many heads or toilets on a ship.
And one says, occupied women.
Turn to the other and it says, occupied men.
And we just honor it.
And I got all my crew together.
And I had officers, female officers.
We hadn't gotten the female enlisted yet.
And I said, look, here are my rules.
You know, we're adults, and there's not going to be any heein and sheein on this ship, and if I find out about it, I'm going to court-martial you.
Now, respect one another, and let's do our jobs, and things will be fine.
I subsequently had some folks, one or the other, get out of the Navy, and they got married, and I'm sure that
Just like Nancy and myself, we weren't supposed to be married, but we eloped to Angleton in 1966.
I just loved her, and she loved me.
There wasn't any reason to go do it.
We just did.
How did you all meet?
On a blind date.
I had the duty in Galveston.
She was a telephone operator in Texas City.
I happened to have the duty.

and Carl Fanning, who was there last night with his two sons, walked in with his wife that was sitting next to him, and Nancy, and introduced us, and I'd had a real rough night the night before, so my eyes were real red, so I was wearing my sunglasses, and I'm sitting there at the duty and all this, and I found out later that when they walked out, Carl asked Nancy, he said, well, what did you think about him?
And she said something to the effect of, well, I don't know, I couldn't see his eyes.
And then we had a date subsequent to that in Galveston, I don't know how familiar you are with Galveston, but the

the what is now the opera house used to be a movie theater and we had our first date and it was a you know there's a post between us and and then we went to a party or something and I told her I loved her and she says oh yeah I understand I've got your routine and and then it just worked out and it's 36 years ago well actually I was 30 I was 65 so so you what year in school were you
I was a junior when we got married.
I was a sophomore when this happened, a junior.
Then you moved off campus?
Nope.
I stayed on campus.
As a matter of fact, here I was, the Corps Commander.
I got married in December of 66, and in January I became the commander down there.
And I wasn't the only one that was married.
And we were kind of under an obligation not to be married, but other folks had done it, and you just didn't advertise it.
Nancy and I didn't.
But the rest of the cadets down there thought I was really a he-man.
Because I'd go out after I finished studying at night about 10 o'clock and go over to Lamarck.
And Nancy and I had a room in her house that we were living in.
And then I'd get up early the next morning and these guys said, that guy Picket Man, he's out all night.
And God, look at him.
This guy is amazing.
And of course, my grades just went up.
Exponentially, because now all of a sudden, I have the potential of having a family to support.
We didn't have one.
Our daughter was born five years later, but it was, yeah.
All right, so when you come up then for final review, who is here from your family and your loved ones?
Well, my parents were here, and Nancy was here, and I think my in-laws, I think, came up.
My brother was going to school here, so I know he was here.
He was in Seagram 7.
And I think that was pretty much it.
And where were you guys in the order?
I think we were last.
Last?
I think we were tail end Charlie.
But nobody made fun of you?
No, no.
We always felt very comfortable on campus.
Everybody except us.
You know, you're an Aggie.
So it doesn't matter.
You know, it doesn't matter as far as I could tell.
What creates that attitude?
I don't know.
I think people that come here come here knowing that's the way it is.
And I think that's what fosters it.
It's a pride.
It's an association with folks that you know before you ever come here.
So all it really
All you really do is resubstantiate that the longer you're here and around people that are here.
Did it matter what your ancestry was or your family?
Never, never.
You know, I can't remember ever, ever having anyone say anything that was derogatory.
I mean, about anyone or anything.
You know, well...
Ernie Catanzaro, or Sonny Catanzaro that I was just talking about was of Mexican, Hispanic descent.
No one ever called him a Whitback or any of that kind of stuff.
I'm trying to think, I don't think we had any blacks here that I can recall.
We may have, at least in 65.
Somewhere about then is when it came in, but
But that wouldn't have been anything.
I mean, I just, it never just, it never occurred to me one way or the other and it wouldn't have mattered one way or the other.

I just, I think it's just something that people come here with and it just grows while you're here and then as you get older and it just, you know, you look back on it and it's just the right thing to do.
Ethical thing.
As you go through commencement, every name is called, every hand is shaken.
Yes, sir.
We're all in our Navy dress whites and Vietnam is already
Oh, Vietnam's still going on big time.
What kind of world did you think you were going out into?
Well, my first trip in the Merchant Marines was to Vietnam, and I came back from that.

I stayed in the Merchant Marines long enough, you know, because I wanted to fly combat, and, you know, and our whole class used to talk about that, you know, even as freshmen, that, you know, we're here to serve.
You know, that's what we're being trained to do, and, you know,
And we had a whole bunch of folks that went off to Vietnam.
My roommate, Terry Archer, I had no idea about this.
We were in Naples, Florida about two months ago with him, he and his wife.
And the gals had gone off shopping.
And Terry had this Vietnam book laying on his desk there.
And I thought Terry, he was a great golfer.
He was on the golf team here and really a super golfer.
And I said, Terry, what the heck are you really doing in Vietnam?
It's funny, he and I had never talked about that because we'd seen each other for years.
And we're both sitting in the lounge.
She says, well, he says, you know, I was at Anlock and here and there.
And I said, I thought you were doing golf courses or something.
He says, no.
And I said, boy, you must have really seen some action then.
And he says, yeah.
And I said, I was talking about some friends of mine that got wounded.
And I said, you're lucky to get out of there without getting shot.
And he said, I did get shot.
And I said, Terry, you never told me this.
Well, it turns out he got shot in the rear end.
And he was afraid that his dad, who was a colonel, like my dad, would say, if you got, those old guys, you got shot in the back or the rear, you were running.
And he says, all I did was just turn and jump over to get behind something.
He said, I only went about four feet.
He said, I was always afraid my dad would think I was a coward, which is kind of interesting.
How well prepared did you think A&M had made you for that real world?
Let me tell you, that's a great story.
Since graduation, I picked up two master's degrees.
I've been two fellowships at Harvard and in national security at the Kennedy School of Government.
And I will tell you, and I've gone to the war college, the Naval War College, and it did a wonderful job, absolutely wonderful job.
Yeah, it was just awesome.
What did it do that was right?
Well, one, I learned right from wrong.
I always use the term do the right thing.
I learned that here.
Regardless, stand up for what you think is right.
And if you're right, you may lose in the short term, but in the long term, you're going to be right.
And it's almost, I used to tell, I still tell Nancy, I said, you know, sometimes I think people just,
just want to push me along so you want to see what I'll do next.
You know, because I've always kind of taken things on that I don't like status quo.
I like to make things better.
And like women in combat, I didn't have a problem with that.
And it was going to work and it was going to work right.
And we've had some other things.
We fight fires in the Navy now, I changed.
In fact, I was talking to some firemen in Galveston yesterday about this, is that you don't, you know, we don't go running into buildings.
Like, you know, why do firemen feel they have to run into a house that's already been evacuated?
You know, you want to contain it, and you're not going to save a lot of stuff anyway.
You know, don't risk, we do some funny things, you know, under a guise of,

being brave but we need to be careful now in this what just happened those guys were absolutely doing the right thing I mean who knew that the towers were going to fall and look at all the people they saved and they are heroes been on a ship and in other areas we know people are out and all this there is stuff we'll let it go so I've always so it's that kind of it's that kind of stuff it this school allows you to think on your two on your feet I think the stress they put us through and so forth in the Corps was good uh
Was there good attention to being an individual?
I felt like an individual, but I also felt like I was part of a team.
Teamwork to me has always been important.
I don't need superstars.
In the Navy, I used to tell my folks that, like on an aircraft carrier, I said, you know, I don't need a bunch of, you know, a couple of superstars.
What I need are 6,000 folks that are all pulling the same direction.
and folks that will come in and tell you, hey, Admiral, that's not the right thing to do, or Captain, that's not the right thing to do, and stand there and take a wrath.
But then, kind of like you mentioned with River Rudder, you know, I've made a lot of phone calls after it was over and said, hey, listen, come back in here.
You were right.
I was wrong.
If you were hired now as a consultant to advise Texas A&M's leadership
about what to do or not to do in the future, what advice would you give them?
What should A&M emphasize?
Let me just give you a philosophy that I have discovered over the years and partly by the two fellowships at Harvard because you get a chance to dialogue on this.
They were national security seminars.
So you're generally talking about Russia and how we should send $3 billion there.
There's some pretty high-powered folks coming there and lecture.

You know, every time we do this, or we did it as a group, and there were 30 military senior officers and 30 senior civilians from industry and from the Civil Service, we always came back with the most important national security issue being education.
We have somehow got to figure out how to get into these back areas and get people that understand
that may not even have the grades, only because they haven't had a chance to have the grades.
They've had to do other stuff.
And somehow get those youngsters to be a productive member of society.
And that takes education.
Education is the absolute key to the security of this country and the security of this world.
Because the more you can educate people, the more people are educated in the right way, the less apt they are to be Osama bin Laden's, to be the Taliban.
I mean, look what he's doing with the women over there.
The reason he's doing it is because if you don't educate them, you don't have to worry about them.
You know, they consider themselves stupid.
And that's something we've got to do in this country.
And right here in Texas, you know, you don't have to drive very many streets in Galveston to see people that haven't had that opportunity.
Or in Houston, it's all over the place.
People that are smart don't go rob banks in 7-Elevens and those kinds of things.
And somehow we've got to find a way to do that.
And I don't know if it's a prep school
to get someone ready to go to school here or what?
But that would be a vision that I would have is how do we take this wonderful stuff that we do and get it down to the lowest levels to people that on just the front, they don't have the credentials
But inside they do, and they just haven't had the chance to do it.
Because, you know, we always, the Colin Powell's, what do they do?
They move out of the areas.
And all of them do.
I mean, all these folks move out of the areas because they somehow were able to bring themselves up, but we need that leadership down there to get the rest of the crowd out.
As you look back on your A&M years, to whom are you most grateful, feel indebtedness to?
If they were all here today, to whom would you most want to express your appreciation?
Probably to a fellow by the name of Jim Hopkins, who was my navigation instructor.
He was a really tough, tough taskmaster.
And to Mrs. Thiel, who was my Spanish instructor.
In a school that was all boys, all men, Mrs. Thiel brought almost a mother side to things.
Is that T-H-E-I-L?
T-H-E-I-L.
Her husband is a doctor in Galveston and is a...
I'm an admiral in the Texas Navy and he's the CNO of the Texas Navy.
And really a great lady.
I haven't seen her in probably 30 years, but she's a wonderful lady.
But those two folks probably...
more than anybody else.
I'm about through with the questions.
Are there any things we haven't covered that we should have?
No, I think I've probably talked way too much.
I haven't talked like this in years.

If someone walks up to you and gives you a check for a million dollars with one condition, you must pass it on to Texas A&M, but you decide the use to be made of that money, what would you want done with that money?
I would start a school, just like I said, a prep school that would...
that would go into the inner reaches.
I'm not talking about just blacks or Hispanics.
I'm talking about Caucasians.
I would start some kind of a school, prep school, that would get people ready to meet that top 10%, even though they haven't had a chance in their high school years to do it.
Because I think there's a...
I think there's that whole group of society out there that we're overlooking, that somehow we have to bring into this world that we live in so we don't become elitist.
That's just.
All right, my last question then.
What feelings do you carry in your heart for Texas A&M?
Great love.
Great love.
It's a wonderful place.
